The steps involved in a Statistical Analysis

  • What data to collect? This depends on what the research question is and who asks it.
  • How to collect data in a clever way? Design of experiments, computer simulations.
  • How to organize your data? In paper notebooks? files? data bases?
  • How to describe your data? File format and size. File content. Statistical descriptive summaries.
  • How to analyse data? Relationships, statistical inference

A dataset is a collection of data (i.e., numbers, qualifiers, pieces of information) that usually come from actual observations collected on cases, obtained by sampling a population.

Each row corresponds to the observations (values) of a few variables (e.g., height or weight) on one given element (case) of that population. Each column represents a particular variable.

The data set may comprise data for one or more members, corresponding to the number of rows, and called the sample size.

You should clearly identify the:

  • Population: the collection of all individuals or items or objects under consideration in a statistical study, usually determined by what we want to know.
  • Cases: the members, objects, units, subjects or individuals from the population, from which information (i.e., data) is collected.
  • IDs: the identification code of each case.
  • Sample: a subset of the population.
  • Sample size, \(n\): number of cases/observations in the sample.
  • Variable: a characteristic of the cases (measured, collected, recorded or counted).
  • Number of variables, \(p\): the total number of variable.

Random Variables

The type of a variable is either categorical or quantitative.

  • A qualitative or categorical variable places an individual into one of several categories.
  • A quantitative variable takes numerical values, for which arithmetic operations such as averaging make sense.

We dissociate two types of quantitative random variables:

  • Discrete random variables can take only distinct, separate values.
  • Continuous random variables can take any values in some interval (low, high)

Let’s decide what type of variables are in the MATH1041 survey dataset. If needed type survey.df$variablename or simply variablename to see the values the variables takes.

Numerical summaries for one variable

Numerical summaries for a categorical variable

We can summarise one categorical variable using table of frequencies which corresponds to a list of the possible categories (even those not observed) together with their counts, percent or proportion of cases in each category.

Consider the survey question “Did you watch the Australian Open Women Tennis Final (yes/no)?”, a table of frequencies is produced as follows

table(tennis.tv)
## tennis.tv
##   0   1 
## 153  56

If we wanted percentages, we would use

prop.table(table(tennis.tv)) * 100
## tennis.tv
##        0        1 
## 73.20574 26.79426

and if we wanted both counts and percentages to be displayed

tbl <- table(tennis.tv)
cbind(tbl, prop.table(tbl) * 100)
##   tbl         
## 0 153 73.20574
## 1  56 26.79426

Numerical summaries for a quantitative variable

Is it a good idea to compute a table of frequencies or percentages for a quantitative variable? Why? Why not?

When summarising a quantitative variable numerically, we often make sure to include measures of:

  • the location (where most of the data are), and
  • the spread (or variability) of the data.

A useful measure of the location is the mean which mathematically, if let \(\boldsymbol{x}= \{ x_1, \ldots, x_n \}\) represent the \(n\) observations (the data points), is calculated as: \[ \textrm{mean}(\boldsymbol{x}) = \frac{x_1 + \cdots + x_n}{n}.\] An alternative to the mean is the median, it corresponds to the middle value. If we sort the observations into \(x_{(1)} \leq \cdots \leq x_{(n)}\), the median is computed as \[\textrm{median}(\boldsymbol{x}) = x_{(n+1)/2} \textrm{ if } n \textrm{ is odd} \quad \textrm{and} \quad \textrm{median}(\boldsymbol{x}) = \frac{1}{2}\left( x_{n/2} + x_{(n+1)/2}\right) \textrm{ if } n \textrm{ is even.}\]

WARNING The mean can be grossly affected by unusually large (or small) data values that tend to be quite far away from the bulk of the data.

In R, the mean() and median() functions, as their name indicate, calculate the mean and median values from a vector of observations.

Use these functions to calculate the mean and median of the UNSW satisfaction score.

mean(unsw.satisfaction)
## [1] 4.507703
median(unsw.satisfaction)
## [1] 4.5

The median splits the data into two groups which contain roughly \(50\%\) of the data.

Quartiles divide the data into four groups which each contain roughly \(25\%\) (a quarter) of the data. \(Q_1\) and \(Q_3\) are known as the first and third quantile. \(Q_2\) is just the median.

A useful measure for spread could be the Inter-quartiles range (IQR).

Quartiles and inter-quartile range

Other useful measures are the standard deviation \(\textrm{sd}(\boldsymbol{x})\) and the variance \(\textrm{var}(\boldsymbol{x}) = \textrm{sd}(\boldsymbol{x})^2\). We voluntarily omit the mathematical expressions, we will use R to calculate them directly.

In R, the quantile(x=..., probs=...) function computes the quantiles of a vector given in x with probability probs. For example, \(Q_1\) is found by selecting probs=0.25. The standard deviation and variance are respectively computed using the sd() and var() functions.

Use these functions to calculate the IQR, standard deviation and variance of the UNSW satisfaction score.

diff(quantile(unsw.satisfaction, c(0.25, 0.75)))
## 75% 
##   1
c( sd(unsw.satisfaction), sd(unsw.satisfaction)^2, var(unsw.satisfaction))
## [1] 1.038383 1.078239 1.078239

Another useful function is summary(), which gives the following 5-number summary

summary(unsw.satisfaction)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   1.610   4.000   4.500   4.508   5.000   8.000

Graphical summaries for one variable

Graphical summaries for a categorical variable

Bar charts are used to summarise categorical random variables. In R, this is done using the barplot() function and below is an example with the tennis.tv variable.

barplot(table(tennis.tv),
        names.arg=c("No", "Yes"),
        main="Did you watch the Australian Open Women Tennis Final?",
        xlab="Answer", ylab="Counts",col="darkred")

The above plot was done in base R, now let’s be fancy and use ggplot! We require to load the ggplot2 library (and install it if needed).

#install.packages("ggplot2")
library(ggplot2)
We start by creating a data.frame object as follows 
tennis <- data.frame(answer=c("No", "Yes"), count=as.vector(tbl))
tennis
##   answer count
## 1     No   153
## 2    Yes    56
p <- ggplot(data=tennis, aes(x=answer, y=count)) +
            geom_bar(stat="identity", color="blue",fill="steelblue") +
            geom_text(aes(label=count), vjust=1.6, color="white", size=8.5)
p

Take the time to play with the arguments to see what each of them does.

We could improve the plot further by, for example, doing the following

p + 
  ggtitle("Did you watch the Australian Open Women \n Tennis Final?") +
  xlab("Answer") + 
  ylab("Count") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(color="red", size=20, face="bold.italic"),
        axis.text = element_text(size=16),
        axis.title.x = element_text(color="blue", size=20, face="bold"),
        axis.title.y = element_text(color="#993333", size=20, face="bold"))

Graphical summaries for a quantitative variable

Boxplots and Histograms are used to summarise quantitative random variables. In R, the corresponding functions are boxplot() and hist(). Below is an example applied to the UNSW satisfaction score, using the ggplot2 library.

sat <- data.frame(satisfaction = unsw.satisfaction)
p2 <- ggplot(data=sat, aes(x="", y=satisfaction)) +
             geom_boxplot(fill = "white", colour = "#3366FF",
                          outlier.colour = "red", outlier.shape = 1) +
             ylab("Score") + 
             xlab("") + 
             theme_bw()
p2

Note: the length of the whiskers is by default 1.5 times IQR, the argument coef in geom_boxplot() controls that value.

Once again, take the time to play with the arguments to see what each of them does.

We could super-impose the data points to the plot

p2 + geom_jitter(width = 0.2) + 
     theme(axis.text = element_text(size=16),
           axis.title.y = element_text(color="#993333", size=20, face="bold"))

… and now plotting a histogram

p3 <- ggplot(data=sat, aes(satisfaction)) +
             geom_histogram(fill = "#69b3a2", colour = "purple", bins=10, linewidth=2) +
             xlab("Score") + 
             ylab("Count") + 
             theme_classic() +
             theme(axis.text = element_text(size=16),
                   axis.title.y = element_text(color="magenta", size=20, face="bold"))
p3

Numerical summaries for two variables

Numerical summaries for two categorical variables

In this case we use a 2-way table of frequencies, which we compute using the table() function, like when we add only one variable. Let’s consider the variables sex and stress which we have agreed to be categorical.

table(sex, stress)
##         stress
## sex      Not at all Slightly Moderately Very Extremely
##   Male            9       24         23    9         3
##   Female          9       38         61   18        10

Adding proportions:

tbl2 <- table(sex, stress)
round(prop.table(tbl2, margin =2),3) # for column
##         stress
## sex      Not at all Slightly Moderately  Very Extremely
##   Male        0.500    0.387      0.274 0.333     0.231
##   Female      0.500    0.613      0.726 0.667     0.769
round(prop.table(tbl2, margin =1),3) # for row
##         stress
## sex      Not at all Slightly Moderately  Very Extremely
##   Male        0.132    0.353      0.338 0.132     0.044
##   Female      0.066    0.279      0.449 0.132     0.074

For fancier table see e.g., tabyl().

Numerical summaries for one categorical and one quantitative variable

Here we compute a 5-number summary for each group/category.

summary(hair.cost[sex=="Female"])
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##     0.0    30.0    55.0   102.9   122.5   600.0       5
summary(hair.cost[sex=="Male"])
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##     0.0    15.0    25.0    56.3    30.0  2000.0       5

Graphical summaries for two variables

Graphical summaries for two categorical variables

When we have two categorical variables, we use a clustered bar chart. The ggplot2 library makes this kind of plot easy, and in this case we use the geom_bar() function.

Again, we start by creating a data.frame object. 
SS <- data.frame(stress=rep(colnames(tbl2), each=2), 
                 sex = c(rep(rownames(tbl2), 5)),
                 count=as.vector(tbl2))
SS
##        stress    sex count
## 1  Not at all   Male     9
## 2  Not at all Female     9
## 3    Slightly   Male    24
## 4    Slightly Female    38
## 5  Moderately   Male    23
## 6  Moderately Female    61
## 7        Very   Male     9
## 8        Very Female    18
## 9   Extremely   Male     3
## 10  Extremely Female    10
and then proceed to plot 
p4 <- ggplot(data=SS, aes(x=stress, y=count, fill=sex)) +
             geom_bar(stat="identity", position="dodge") +
             ggtitle("Are you stressed?") +
             ylab("Count") + 
             xlab("Stress") + 
             theme_classic() +
             theme(axis.text = element_text(size=12),
                   axis.title = element_text(color="magenta", size=20))
p4

Graphical summaries with two quantitative variables

The easiest way to display two quantitative random variables is via a scatterplot. Below we use the geomm_point() function to plot the average number of hours of sleep per night (hours.slept) as a function of age (age).

AH <- data.frame(age=age, hours=hours.sleep)
head(AH, 10)
##    age hours
## 1   43     6
## 2   23     8
## 3   22     7
## 4   NA     5
## 5   22     7
## 6   22     3
## 7   NA     7
## 8   21     7
## 9   NA     6
## 10  21     7
p6 <- ggplot(data=AH, aes(x=age, y=hours.sleep)) +
             ggtitle("Hours slept as function of age") +
             ylab("Hours slept") + 
             xlab("Age") + 
             theme(axis.text = element_text(size=16),
                   axis.title = element_text(color="magenta", size=20))
p6 + geom_point(shape = 21, colour = "pink", fill = "black", size = 3, stroke = 3)

Once again, take the time to play with the arguments to see what each of them does.

We can change the type of point in the scatterplot as a function of a third, categorical, variable.

AH$sex <- sex
head(AH,10)
##    age hours    sex
## 1   43     6 Female
## 2   23     8   Male
## 3   22     7 Female
## 4   NA     5 Female
## 5   22     7 Female
## 6   22     3   Male
## 7   NA     7   Male
## 8   21     7 Female
## 9   NA     6   Male
## 10  21     7 Female
p6 + geom_jitter(aes(shape=factor(sex), colour = factor(sex), size=2)) +
     scale_x_continuous(limits = c(18, 45)) +
     scale_y_continuous(limits = c(1, 12)) +
     scale_colour_discrete("Sex") +
     guides(size = "none", shape = "none") +
     theme(legend.text = element_text(size=16))

Numerical summaries with two quantitative variables

Correlation is a special form of dependence (association) between two quantitative variables. The correlation coefficient is a number that measures the association between two quantities, indicating the strength and the direction of the linear statistical relationship between the variables.

We denote the (Pearson) Coefficient of correlation by \(r\) and for any data set \[ -1 \leq r \leq 1.\] It is interpreted as follows:

  • \(r\) close to 1 \(\Leftrightarrow\) strong positive linear relationship.
  • \(r\) close to -1 \(\Leftrightarrow\) strong negative linear relationship.
  • \(r\) close to 0 \(\Leftrightarrow\) weak or non-existent linear relationship.

Examples of correlation between two variables

In R, the correlation between two variables, say x and y is computed using cor(x,y). If the variables are stored in the same object (a matrix or a data.frame), then providing the column indicator is sufficient. E.g., cor(mat[,1:2]).

Look at the scatterplot of the average number of hours of sleep per night and age, what is your guess for the correlation between these two variables? Use R to check your intuition.

cor(AH[,1:2]) # Same as cor(AH[,1], AH[,1]) . Both produces NA!!!
##       age hours
## age     1    NA
## hours  NA     1
cor(na.omit(AH)[,1:2])
##              age      hours
## age   1.00000000 0.07026975
## hours 0.07026975 1.00000000
